00:00:34.792 --> 00:00:40.990
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:40.990 --> 00:00:43.240
SIMON SINEK: Thanks.

00:00:43.240 --> 00:00:46.390
So I thought I'd share with
you some new stuff that I'm

00:00:46.390 --> 00:00:49.600
working on because it's
fun, and then we'll

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:51.650
spend most of the
time just doing Q&amp;A

00:00:51.650 --> 00:00:53.282
because that's also fun.

00:00:53.282 --> 00:00:55.240
So I'm working on a new
book, and I've recently

00:00:55.240 --> 00:01:01.990
become completely smitten
by game theory, specifically

00:01:01.990 --> 00:01:04.150
finite and infinite games.

00:01:04.150 --> 00:01:05.830
In game theory,
there are two types

00:01:05.830 --> 00:01:07.690
of games-- finite
and infinite games.

00:01:07.690 --> 00:01:11.860
A finite game is defined as
known players, fixed rules,

00:01:11.860 --> 00:01:14.707
and an agreed upon
objective, like baseball.

00:01:14.707 --> 00:01:15.790
We all agree to the rules.

00:01:15.790 --> 00:01:18.340
We all agree that whoever has
more runs at the end of nine

00:01:18.340 --> 00:01:21.070
innings is the winner, and the
game ends and we all go home.

00:01:21.070 --> 00:01:22.990
Nobody ever says, if we can
just play three more innings

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:24.823
and then we can come
back from this deficit.

00:01:24.823 --> 00:01:26.560
It doesn't happen that way.

00:01:26.560 --> 00:01:32.710
An infinite game is defined
as known and unknown players.

00:01:32.710 --> 00:01:36.310
The rules are changeable,
and the objective

00:01:36.310 --> 00:01:40.240
is to keep the game in play
to perpetuate the game.

00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:42.515
When you pit a finite player
versus a finite player,

00:01:42.515 --> 00:01:43.390
the system is stable.

00:01:43.390 --> 00:01:45.610
Baseball is stable.

00:01:45.610 --> 00:01:49.120
When you hit an infinite player
versus an infinite player,

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:53.650
the system is also stable,
like the Cold War was stable

00:01:53.650 --> 00:01:56.850
because there cannot be a winner
and there cannot be a loser.

00:01:56.850 --> 00:01:59.020
So we just try and
keep the game in play.

00:01:59.020 --> 00:02:00.730
And in infinite
games, because there

00:02:00.730 --> 00:02:02.890
are no winners and
losers, what happens

00:02:02.890 --> 00:02:04.990
is players drop out
of the game when

00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:09.610
they run out of the will or the
resources to continue to play.

00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:12.940
So technically, the United
States didn't win the Cold War.

00:02:12.940 --> 00:02:14.980
The Soviets dropped out
because they ran out

00:02:14.980 --> 00:02:17.860
of the resources or the
will to continue to play.

00:02:17.860 --> 00:02:19.780
Problems arise,
however, when you

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:22.532
pit a finite player
versus an infinite player,

00:02:22.532 --> 00:02:24.490
because one is playing
to win and the other one

00:02:24.490 --> 00:02:26.530
is playing to keep playing.

00:02:26.530 --> 00:02:29.440
So invariably, what happens is
the finite player will always

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:31.600
find themselves in a quagmire.

00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:33.970
So this was the United
States and Vietnam.

00:02:33.970 --> 00:02:36.370
The United States
was fighting to win,

00:02:36.370 --> 00:02:39.340
and the North Vietnamese
were fighting to survive--

00:02:39.340 --> 00:02:41.830
very different set of standards.

00:02:41.830 --> 00:02:44.230
This was the Soviet
Union in Afghanistan.

00:02:44.230 --> 00:02:46.670
The Soviets were fighting
to beet the Mujaheddin,

00:02:46.670 --> 00:02:49.480
and the Mujaheddin would fight
for as long as is necessary.

00:02:49.480 --> 00:02:51.790
And invariably, what
happens is the finite player

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:53.206
will find themselves
in a quagmire

00:02:53.206 --> 00:02:55.359
until they drop out of the
game and leave the game,

00:02:55.359 --> 00:02:57.400
because they run out of
the will or the resources

00:02:57.400 --> 00:02:59.800
to stay in the game.

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:02.240
So this gets me thinking.

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:03.970
Let's look at business.

00:03:03.970 --> 00:03:09.790
The game of business
is an infinite game.

00:03:09.790 --> 00:03:12.070
It obeys all the rules.

00:03:12.070 --> 00:03:13.870
There are known and
unknown players.

00:03:13.870 --> 00:03:16.690
You don't know all the
competitors, necessarily,

00:03:16.690 --> 00:03:18.610
in one industry to another.

00:03:18.610 --> 00:03:19.690
The rules are changeable.

00:03:19.690 --> 00:03:21.820
We haven't all agreed
what the rules are,

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:25.507
and there is no winning
the game of business.

00:03:25.507 --> 00:03:26.590
The game just perpetuates.

00:03:26.590 --> 00:03:28.150
In fact, the game
of business has

00:03:28.150 --> 00:03:31.090
existed longer than every single
company on the planet today,

00:03:31.090 --> 00:03:34.750
and it will outlast every single
company on the planet today.

00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:37.720
If you look at the Dow Index,
the 30-something-odd companies

00:03:37.720 --> 00:03:40.690
that make up the Dow Index,
something like 70% or 80%

00:03:40.690 --> 00:03:45.850
of those companies are
35 years or younger.

00:03:45.850 --> 00:03:50.620
So it gets me thinking, if
you listen to the language

00:03:50.620 --> 00:03:55.030
that companies use, they don't
know what game they're in.

00:03:55.030 --> 00:03:57.955
They talk about being
number one, talk

00:03:57.955 --> 00:04:00.580
about beating their
competition, based

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:03.370
on what agreed upon
criteria, based

00:04:03.370 --> 00:04:05.410
on what agreed upon time frame?

00:04:05.410 --> 00:04:06.840
Is it market share?

00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:07.680
Is it profits?

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:08.890
Is it revenues?

00:04:08.890 --> 00:04:09.610
Square footage?

00:04:09.610 --> 00:04:10.960
Number of employees?

00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:11.460
Over what?

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:14.044
One month, five months, six
months, a year, five years,

00:04:14.044 --> 00:04:15.460
10 years, the life
of the company?

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:17.500
I haven't agreed to those rules.

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:20.019
And so companies can
arbitrarily declare themselves

00:04:20.019 --> 00:04:22.560
number one in anything they
want if they set the standards

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:24.391
and the time frames.

00:04:24.391 --> 00:04:26.890
And the only reason we do these
things on annualized basis--

00:04:26.890 --> 00:04:30.220
we tend to compare ourselves
to other organizations

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:33.029
annually-- is only because
we pay taxes annually.

00:04:33.029 --> 00:04:34.570
If we pay taxes
every 18 months, that

00:04:34.570 --> 00:04:36.170
would be sort of the standard.

00:04:36.170 --> 00:04:39.520
But again, we still haven't
agreed what the metrics

00:04:39.520 --> 00:04:41.470
are to be number one.

00:04:41.470 --> 00:04:45.360
That means that companies that
are playing the infinite game

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:47.110
are playing against
most of the others who

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:49.660
are playing the finite game
means those finite companies

00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:52.600
find themselves in a quagmire.

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:55.240
Almost every single
bankruptcy-- not almost every,

00:04:55.240 --> 00:04:57.040
every single
bankruptcy-- is a company

00:04:57.040 --> 00:04:58.750
that's run out of the will
or the resources to play.

00:04:58.750 --> 00:04:59.833
They drop out of the game.

00:04:59.833 --> 00:05:01.180
The game will persist.

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:02.770
Another company will
fill their space.

00:05:02.770 --> 00:05:06.970
It's not like the business
stops or the industry ends.

00:05:06.970 --> 00:05:10.300
And the companies that are
playing the infinite game

00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:13.270
will frustrate those finite
players, which I absolutely

00:05:13.270 --> 00:05:14.560
adore.

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:19.594
So I spoke at an education
summit for Microsoft.

00:05:19.594 --> 00:05:21.510
I also spoke in an
education summit for Apple.

00:05:21.510 --> 00:05:25.390
Now, I would say about 70%
to 80% of the executives

00:05:25.390 --> 00:05:27.730
at Microsoft spent
about 70% to 80%

00:05:27.730 --> 00:05:35.250
of their PowerPoints talking
about how to beat Apple.

00:05:35.250 --> 00:05:38.040
At the Apple summit,
100% of the executives

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:41.400
spent 100% of their
presentations talking

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:44.970
about how to help teachers teach
and how to help students learn.

00:05:44.970 --> 00:05:48.060
One was obsessed with their
journey, with their vision,

00:05:48.060 --> 00:05:48.887
with their cause.

00:05:48.887 --> 00:05:50.970
The other one was obsessed
with their competition.

00:05:50.970 --> 00:05:52.620
Guess who's stuck in quagmire?

00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:56.102
Guess who's frustrated
by their competition?

00:05:56.102 --> 00:05:58.560
So at the end of my talk at
Microsoft, they gave me a gift.

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:00.630
They gave me the new
Zune, when it was a thing.

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:06.120
And I have to tell
you, this was one

00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:08.400
of the most remarkable,
beautiful pieces of technology

00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:09.450
I've ever used.

00:06:09.450 --> 00:06:11.310
The UI was gorgeous.

00:06:11.310 --> 00:06:15.120
The design of the actual
hardware was beautiful.

00:06:15.120 --> 00:06:18.720
It was logical in the
way I could use it.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:20.494
It was intuitive.

00:06:20.494 --> 00:06:21.660
It was absolutely fantastic.

00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:23.610
Now, it didn't work with iTunes,
which means I couldn't use it.

00:06:23.610 --> 00:06:25.193
That's a different
problem altogether,

00:06:25.193 --> 00:06:27.640
but this was a magical
piece of technology.

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:29.790
So at the end of
my talk at Apple,

00:06:29.790 --> 00:06:33.420
I'm sharing a cab with one of
the senior Apple executives,

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:35.400
sort of an employee
number 12 kind of guy,

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:37.029
and I decide to stir the pot.

00:06:37.029 --> 00:06:39.570
So I turned to him and I said,
you know, I spoke at Microsoft

00:06:39.570 --> 00:06:42.090
and they gave me the new
Zune and it is so much

00:06:42.090 --> 00:06:44.810
better than your iPod Touch.

00:06:44.810 --> 00:06:48.360
And he turns to me and
he says, I have no doubt.

00:06:48.360 --> 00:06:50.820
Conversation over.

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:53.130
Because the infinite
player understands

00:06:53.130 --> 00:06:55.860
sometimes your product is
better and sometimes it's not.

00:06:55.860 --> 00:06:58.650
Sometimes you're ahead and
sometimes you're behind.

00:06:58.650 --> 00:07:01.080
The goal is not to
beat your competitor.

00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:03.850
The goal is to outlast
your competitor.

00:07:03.850 --> 00:07:07.200
What you find is that the
infinite players don't actually

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:08.790
compete against
their competition.

00:07:08.790 --> 00:07:10.422
They compete against themselves.

00:07:10.422 --> 00:07:11.880
The finite players
are the ones who

00:07:11.880 --> 00:07:13.530
wake up every day trying
to beat somebody else.

00:07:13.530 --> 00:07:14.730
The infinite
players the ones who

00:07:14.730 --> 00:07:16.850
say, how can we be a better
version of ourselves,

00:07:16.850 --> 00:07:18.600
how can we advance our
metrics, how can we

00:07:18.600 --> 00:07:21.060
make our product more
refined, more beautiful

00:07:21.060 --> 00:07:23.010
than they were last week.

00:07:23.010 --> 00:07:26.345
It's totally fine to
study our competition.

00:07:26.345 --> 00:07:27.720
Tactically, there's
nothing wrong

00:07:27.720 --> 00:07:29.830
with knowing what our
competitors are doing.

00:07:29.830 --> 00:07:32.490
But the number of companies
that study their competition

00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:34.770
strategically blows my mind.

00:07:34.770 --> 00:07:36.720
They look at what their
competition is doing,

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:39.120
and they make sudden,
sharp left and right turns

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:40.710
to change the course
of their company,

00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:42.930
based on the movement
of their competition.

00:07:42.930 --> 00:07:44.010
That's the point.

00:07:44.010 --> 00:07:48.435
That's what wastes resources,
the constant changing

00:07:48.435 --> 00:07:50.560
of your mind, the constant
going in this direction,

00:07:50.560 --> 00:07:53.430
that direction, based on the
wind of your competition--

00:07:53.430 --> 00:07:55.860
assuming that they know
what they're doing.

00:07:55.860 --> 00:07:57.930
I find that fascinating.

00:07:57.930 --> 00:07:59.850
And the number of
companies that play finite

00:07:59.850 --> 00:08:02.419
is the vast, vast,
vast majority.

00:08:02.419 --> 00:08:03.960
So it begs the
question, how does one

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:06.270
play the infinite game?

00:08:06.270 --> 00:08:09.690
How does one build an
organization constructed

00:08:09.690 --> 00:08:11.160
for the infinite game?

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:14.100
So up here, you have
the infinite game.

00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:15.780
This is where the why exists.

00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:18.240
I talk about the why-- the
purpose, cause, or belief--

00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:19.330
about the organization.

00:08:19.330 --> 00:08:21.720
This is where our values lie.

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:23.400
These are never-changing.

00:08:23.400 --> 00:08:24.540
They are permanent.

00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:27.420
They will outlast all of us,
and they should outlast--

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:29.420
they've been here from
the birth of the company,

00:08:29.420 --> 00:08:31.679
and they should last the
length of the company.

00:08:31.679 --> 00:08:33.929
The infinite stuff, the why
stuff and the value stuff,

00:08:33.929 --> 00:08:38.980
is inherently intangible,
and it's inherently difficult

00:08:38.980 --> 00:08:40.840
to measure.

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:44.240
Now, down here you
have the finite game,

00:08:44.240 --> 00:08:48.540
and this is where
our interests lie.

00:08:48.540 --> 00:08:51.294
This is where what I would
call your "whats" lie.

00:08:51.294 --> 00:08:53.460
This is where our products
lie and things like that.

00:08:53.460 --> 00:08:57.990
It is inherently tangible
and inherently very easy

00:08:57.990 --> 00:08:59.130
to measure.

00:08:59.130 --> 00:09:03.840
Now, the goal is to run all
decisions through our values,

00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:06.300
through our purpose or
cause first, and then

00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:07.410
through our interests.

00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:09.120
So what is a
values-based decision?

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:11.050
What does that even look like?

00:09:11.050 --> 00:09:13.290
So here's a
values-based decision.

00:09:13.290 --> 00:09:20.470
When our military goes into
battle and we shoot a bad guy,

00:09:20.470 --> 00:09:21.930
we will take their injured body.

00:09:21.930 --> 00:09:24.150
We will send our medics
onto the battlefield

00:09:24.150 --> 00:09:27.610
to rescue the injured
body of our enemy.

00:09:27.610 --> 00:09:29.130
We will put them
on our helicopters,

00:09:29.130 --> 00:09:32.520
fly them to our hospitals,
put them in our hospital beds.

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:34.230
Our doctors will
use our medicine

00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:36.060
to nurse them back to health.

00:09:36.060 --> 00:09:38.400
That is not in our interest.

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:43.050
However, that's
kind of who we are.

00:09:43.050 --> 00:09:44.610
It's what defines us.

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:46.710
In other words, we're
wasting our resources

00:09:46.710 --> 00:09:50.070
because our values are
more important than saving

00:09:50.070 --> 00:09:54.000
those resources, doing something
purely in our interests.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:55.470
It's like torture.

00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:58.080
The reason torture
was done offshore

00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:01.140
and the reason we tried
to keep it a secret

00:10:01.140 --> 00:10:04.304
is because everybody kind of
knew it violated our values.

00:10:04.304 --> 00:10:05.970
Because if we were
totally fine with it,

00:10:05.970 --> 00:10:08.469
everybody would be like, just
do it here, it's totally fine.

00:10:08.469 --> 00:10:09.780
Why not somewhere in Wyoming?

00:10:12.895 --> 00:10:13.770
And that's the point.

00:10:13.770 --> 00:10:17.340
So great organizations are
making values-based decisions

00:10:17.340 --> 00:10:21.317
all the time, and then our
interests come into play.

00:10:21.317 --> 00:10:23.400
But the problem is when
you're playing the finite,

00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:25.740
these things get ignored,
and every time we

00:10:25.740 --> 00:10:28.920
make a decision we decide
what we do in a vacuum.

00:10:28.920 --> 00:10:31.170
So your competitor comes
out with a new product.

00:10:31.170 --> 00:10:31.980
How do we react?

00:10:31.980 --> 00:10:35.869
Quickly, come out with
something similar.

00:10:35.869 --> 00:10:37.410
What's going on with
the marketplace,

00:10:37.410 --> 00:10:38.310
and make some other reaction.

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:40.110
What's going on in this
particular country?

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:42.660
And every single decision
we make in a vacuum

00:10:42.660 --> 00:10:43.590
seems perfectly good.

00:10:43.590 --> 00:10:46.982
We're making rational decisions
based on our interests.

00:10:46.982 --> 00:10:48.690
The problem is when
we pull back and look

00:10:48.690 --> 00:10:50.220
at all of the decisions,
all the people we've

00:10:50.220 --> 00:10:52.678
hired, this is what happens
when you only hire people based

00:10:52.678 --> 00:10:54.900
on their resumes, for example.

00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:57.840
Smart guy-- get that
person on board.

00:10:57.840 --> 00:11:00.030
When you pull back,
your culture is a mess,

00:11:00.030 --> 00:11:02.580
and nobody knows
what you stand for.

00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:05.280
The whole idea of making
values-based decisions

00:11:05.280 --> 00:11:07.690
is we can look at almost
all of the decisions.

00:11:07.690 --> 00:11:09.754
Every now and then
one can go sideways.

00:11:09.754 --> 00:11:11.170
But we look at all
the decisions--

00:11:11.170 --> 00:11:12.750
the people you hire,
the things you do,

00:11:12.750 --> 00:11:15.291
the things you believe in, the
things you stand for, anything

00:11:15.291 --> 00:11:15.870
tangible--

00:11:15.870 --> 00:11:18.820
and we can say of you
or your organization,

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:22.140
I know what you stand for.

00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:24.880
I believe what you believe.

00:11:24.880 --> 00:11:27.280
I would like to be a part
of your organization.

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:28.905
I'd like to buy from
your organization.

00:11:28.905 --> 00:11:30.150
This is where loyalty lies.

00:11:30.150 --> 00:11:32.760
But the only way we can judge
each other is down here.

00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:34.410
It's like human beings.

00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:38.370
We want our friends to act and
speak and do the things based

00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:39.037
on who they are.

00:11:39.037 --> 00:11:41.536
We want our friends to be-- you
know that word that's always

00:11:41.536 --> 00:11:43.950
thrown about-- authentic,
which means saying and doing

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:46.380
the things we actually believe.

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:47.910
That's what we mean.

00:11:47.910 --> 00:11:51.030
And the reason is because we
want to know who they are.

00:11:51.030 --> 00:11:53.910
We want them to be predictable.

00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:55.676
I can't see anybody.

00:11:55.676 --> 00:11:58.570
Can we turn the lights back on?

00:11:58.570 --> 00:12:00.340
Was that better for you?

00:12:00.340 --> 00:12:00.960
Oh, sorry.

00:12:04.250 --> 00:12:08.490
But now you can fall
asleep, because I can't see.

00:12:08.490 --> 00:12:09.660
But that's the idea.

00:12:09.660 --> 00:12:10.560
That's the idea.

00:12:10.560 --> 00:12:11.849
So this is what I'm doing.

00:12:11.849 --> 00:12:13.890
I've become fascinated by
this game theory stuff,

00:12:13.890 --> 00:12:15.620
and I'm running it through
all kinds of scenarios.

00:12:15.620 --> 00:12:17.170
I'm looking at relationships,
I'm looking at business,

00:12:17.170 --> 00:12:19.950
I'm looking at politics, I'm
looking at war and nation

00:12:19.950 --> 00:12:22.950
states and how this plays
out in the real world.

00:12:22.950 --> 00:12:24.180
Because the game is the game.

00:12:24.180 --> 00:12:25.554
We don't get to
change the rules.

00:12:25.554 --> 00:12:27.300
Of course, there are
always finite games

00:12:27.300 --> 00:12:28.860
within the infinite.

00:12:28.860 --> 00:12:31.920
It's the difference between
a goal and a vision.

00:12:31.920 --> 00:12:34.025
A goal is 26.2 miles.

00:12:34.025 --> 00:12:35.400
Count the metrics,
count the mile

00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:38.880
markers, and when you reach
the goal the game ends.

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:39.910
It's over.

00:12:39.910 --> 00:12:43.710
The vision is having a crystal
clear sense of what the finish

00:12:43.710 --> 00:12:46.140
line looks like far
from the distance,

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:48.300
but having no idea
how far away it is--

00:12:48.300 --> 00:12:52.320
so far away that for
all practical purposes

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:53.550
we'll never get there.

00:12:53.550 --> 00:12:56.100
Take the United States, the
Declaration of Independence.

00:12:56.100 --> 00:13:01.440
Here is a nation who declared
why we needed our own country.

00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:04.410
And it didn't start off
by complaining or griping

00:13:04.410 --> 00:13:07.120
about the King
and Great Britain.

00:13:07.120 --> 00:13:09.060
It started off with an ideal.

00:13:09.060 --> 00:13:11.535
We believe that all men are
created equal, that all of us

00:13:11.535 --> 00:13:13.410
are endowed with certain,
unalienable rights,

00:13:13.410 --> 00:13:14.780
amongst which include
life, liberty,

00:13:14.780 --> 00:13:16.110
and the pursuit of happiness.

00:13:16.110 --> 00:13:19.140
We'll never actually
get there, but the goal

00:13:19.140 --> 00:13:20.760
is that we will die trying.

00:13:20.760 --> 00:13:23.040
And within that
infinite contest,

00:13:23.040 --> 00:13:24.840
there are many
finite games that we

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:27.900
hope to advance that
infinite contest or even

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:31.650
little infinite games within
that, like civil rights.

00:13:31.650 --> 00:13:33.240
We've never actually
reached the point

00:13:33.240 --> 00:13:34.260
where we have
perfect civil rights,

00:13:34.260 --> 00:13:36.810
but we'll continue to get
better and better and better.

00:13:36.810 --> 00:13:37.710
That's the point.

00:13:37.710 --> 00:13:38.790
It's constant refinement.

00:13:38.790 --> 00:13:40.020
It's kaizen.

00:13:40.020 --> 00:13:43.279
It's no matter how good we
do, we can always do better.

00:13:43.279 --> 00:13:44.820
But the goal is we
have a North Star.

00:13:44.820 --> 00:13:46.695
We have a thing to point
us in the direction.

00:13:46.695 --> 00:13:47.706
It's not random.

00:13:47.706 --> 00:13:49.580
So in the United States,
we have civil rights

00:13:49.580 --> 00:13:52.460
or women's suffrage or
gay rights or education

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:54.740
for everyone or health
care for everyone.

00:13:54.740 --> 00:13:57.950
What form it takes,
it's our way of trying

00:13:57.950 --> 00:14:00.980
to get closer and closer
and closer to the ideal

00:14:00.980 --> 00:14:03.500
upon which the
nation was founded.

00:14:03.500 --> 00:14:06.590
I wish all organizations-- they
don't have to be nation states.

00:14:06.590 --> 00:14:11.030
I wish all organizations did
the same thing-- operated not

00:14:11.030 --> 00:14:14.712
just in their
interests, but also

00:14:14.712 --> 00:14:16.920
have a sense of code or
values and a sense of purpose

00:14:16.920 --> 00:14:18.650
and vision.

00:14:18.650 --> 00:14:19.460
It matters.

00:14:19.460 --> 00:14:21.180
Because we want to
stand for something.

00:14:21.180 --> 00:14:23.090
We want to work for something.

00:14:23.090 --> 00:14:25.670
We want all of our hard work,
the products we produce,

00:14:25.670 --> 00:14:29.580
everything, we want it to
count towards something,

00:14:29.580 --> 00:14:31.820
not simply be against
something or make something

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:33.290
in the short term.

00:14:33.290 --> 00:14:35.840
I see this so often
with senior executives,

00:14:35.840 --> 00:14:39.014
with people who are making more
money than they've ever made.

00:14:39.014 --> 00:14:40.430
They have more
power and influence

00:14:40.430 --> 00:14:41.610
than they've ever had.

00:14:41.610 --> 00:14:42.620
And yet later on
in their careers,

00:14:42.620 --> 00:14:43.730
they don't feel as
successful as they

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:44.970
did when they were a junior.

00:14:44.970 --> 00:14:46.902
When we're junior, the
first promotion we get,

00:14:46.902 --> 00:14:48.860
the first raise we get,
the first bonus we get,

00:14:48.860 --> 00:14:50.550
the first client we
win, whatever it is,

00:14:50.550 --> 00:14:51.860
it's all very exciting.

00:14:51.860 --> 00:14:54.110
We're living down here and
everything's very exciting.

00:14:54.110 --> 00:14:55.400
But after you've had
a bunch of bonuses

00:14:55.400 --> 00:14:56.450
and you've won a
bunch of clients

00:14:56.450 --> 00:14:58.200
and you've had a bunch
of product releases

00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:01.511
and a bunch of promotions,
it's exciting for a little bit.

00:15:01.511 --> 00:15:03.260
Go out for a nice
dinner with your family.

00:15:03.260 --> 00:15:05.960
That's about it, and
then it wears off.

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:08.540
And so what starts to
happen is our work no longer

00:15:08.540 --> 00:15:11.120
feels like it has
any sense of purpose,

00:15:11.120 --> 00:15:13.114
and so we default back
to when we were young.

00:15:13.114 --> 00:15:15.530
We thought, well, when I won
the client, win more clients.

00:15:15.530 --> 00:15:17.030
And when I reach
$1 million dollars,

00:15:17.030 --> 00:15:18.274
get more millions of dollars.

00:15:18.274 --> 00:15:19.940
That gave me the
feeling the first time.

00:15:19.940 --> 00:15:21.356
You'll get with
the feeling again.

00:15:21.356 --> 00:15:22.070
It doesn't.

00:15:22.070 --> 00:15:24.724
That's like winning
one marathon,

00:15:24.724 --> 00:15:25.640
thinking it's amazing.

00:15:25.640 --> 00:15:27.320
You keep running marathons
for the rest of your life,

00:15:27.320 --> 00:15:28.400
and at some point
you're like, why am

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:29.810
I running all these marathons?

00:15:29.810 --> 00:15:31.700
They have to contribute
to something.

00:15:31.700 --> 00:15:33.540
They have to contribute
to something.

00:15:33.540 --> 00:15:35.540
So I'm fascinated by
the companies that

00:15:35.540 --> 00:15:38.960
play the infinite game,
because inherently they

00:15:38.960 --> 00:15:40.310
frustrate their competition.

00:15:40.310 --> 00:15:43.070
For years, Apple frustrated
Microsoft, especially when

00:15:43.070 --> 00:15:44.430
it was run by Steve Ballmer.

00:15:44.430 --> 00:15:47.450
He was a guy who ran the
company based on interests alone

00:15:47.450 --> 00:15:50.060
versus competing against
an organization that

00:15:50.060 --> 00:15:52.520
was doing something bigger--

00:15:52.520 --> 00:15:55.160
Costco versus Wal-Mart,
Southwest Airlines

00:15:55.160 --> 00:15:59.300
versus everybody, organizations
that seem to not care about

00:15:59.300 --> 00:16:01.610
what Wall Street thinks about
the quarter of the year.

00:16:01.610 --> 00:16:04.220
And when you listen to
the language of people

00:16:04.220 --> 00:16:06.799
like Jim Senegal, who's the
founder of Costco, he says,

00:16:06.799 --> 00:16:08.090
I don't care about Wall Street.

00:16:08.090 --> 00:16:11.330
Wall Street's worried about
how my company does in a month

00:16:11.330 --> 00:16:11.937
or in a year.

00:16:11.937 --> 00:16:14.270
I care about what my company
does for the next 50 years.

00:16:14.270 --> 00:16:16.310
That's the company I'm building.

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:18.260
You listen to the language--

00:16:18.260 --> 00:16:21.230
ones who are focused on
teaching kids how to learn

00:16:21.230 --> 00:16:23.630
and helping teachers
how to teach,

00:16:23.630 --> 00:16:26.372
versus how to beat
our competition.

00:16:26.372 --> 00:16:28.080
It makes for a much
more fulfilling life,

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:30.350
and it makes for a much
more realistic existence.

00:16:30.350 --> 00:16:32.016
When your competition
is slightly ahead,

00:16:32.016 --> 00:16:33.730
you think that's OK.

00:16:33.730 --> 00:16:37.340
I can't stay ahead forever
based on some arbitrary

00:16:37.340 --> 00:16:39.080
metrics, anyway.

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:40.410
So that's what I'm working on.

00:16:40.410 --> 00:16:41.118
I think it's fun.

00:16:41.118 --> 00:16:42.270
I think it's interesting.

00:16:42.270 --> 00:16:43.770
We made some changes
even in the way

00:16:43.770 --> 00:16:45.230
we do business based on this.

00:16:45.230 --> 00:16:48.360
We become more
infinitely organized,

00:16:48.360 --> 00:16:50.870
which means we are much
more interested in trends

00:16:50.870 --> 00:16:52.310
than we are in absolutes.

00:16:52.310 --> 00:16:54.765
Because absolutes exist
down here, but ongoing

00:16:54.765 --> 00:16:55.390
exists up here.

00:16:55.390 --> 00:16:56.806
So for example,
let's say you will

00:16:56.806 --> 00:17:00.110
get a bonus if you hit a certain
target by a certain date.

00:17:00.110 --> 00:17:01.790
That target is arbitrary.

00:17:01.790 --> 00:17:04.190
That date is arbitrary.

00:17:04.190 --> 00:17:05.599
Somebody made it up.

00:17:05.599 --> 00:17:08.810
That's how most of our
bonus structures are built--

00:17:08.810 --> 00:17:11.000
on arbitrary numbers
on arbitrary dates.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.640
And let's say that that
person is doing good work

00:17:13.640 --> 00:17:17.210
and building good systems,
but they miss the target.

00:17:17.210 --> 00:17:19.069
They miss the number.

00:17:19.069 --> 00:17:21.810
But if you were to pull back and
look at how they've been doing,

00:17:21.810 --> 00:17:24.200
and you see this
beautiful steady line,

00:17:24.200 --> 00:17:27.170
we can see that they're
doing good work, that they're

00:17:27.170 --> 00:17:28.580
building good systems.

00:17:28.580 --> 00:17:30.530
There's huge stability there.

00:17:30.530 --> 00:17:33.140
They just miss the arbitrary
number on the arbitrary date.

00:17:33.140 --> 00:17:35.084
Give that person a
bonus, because we

00:17:35.084 --> 00:17:37.250
want that person to continue
building those systems.

00:17:37.250 --> 00:17:38.030
And the odds are
they're probably

00:17:38.030 --> 00:17:39.980
at the number two or
three months later, which

00:17:39.980 --> 00:17:42.229
is totally fine because then
it's going to grow, grow,

00:17:42.229 --> 00:17:44.780
and grow, versus the person
who stabs people in the back,

00:17:44.780 --> 00:17:45.954
plays politics.

00:17:45.954 --> 00:17:47.370
Their performance
looks like this.

00:17:47.370 --> 00:17:48.260
There's no stability.

00:17:48.260 --> 00:17:49.310
It's all over the place.

00:17:49.310 --> 00:17:52.169
They happen to meet the
number on an arbitrary date.

00:17:52.169 --> 00:17:53.210
Give that person a bonus?

00:17:53.210 --> 00:17:54.110
Why?

00:17:54.110 --> 00:17:56.390
They're breaking the
company along the way.

00:17:56.390 --> 00:17:58.730
The point is the finite
player only looks

00:17:58.730 --> 00:18:00.170
at these discrete
moments in time,

00:18:00.170 --> 00:18:02.870
and the infinite player
is much more preoccupied

00:18:02.870 --> 00:18:05.104
with the trend of things.

00:18:05.104 --> 00:18:06.770
So in our business,
we become absolutely

00:18:06.770 --> 00:18:07.974
preoccupied with the trend.

00:18:07.974 --> 00:18:09.390
There are some
projects that we've

00:18:09.390 --> 00:18:12.110
wanted to implement
that I wish took a year

00:18:12.110 --> 00:18:13.970
and they took years.

00:18:13.970 --> 00:18:15.871
And it doesn't matter
how much I say,

00:18:15.871 --> 00:18:17.120
I want it done at the end of--

00:18:17.120 --> 00:18:18.170
we missed it.

00:18:18.170 --> 00:18:18.920
But you know what?

00:18:18.920 --> 00:18:20.753
We were building good
systems along the way.

00:18:20.753 --> 00:18:22.784
We just missed a prediction.

00:18:22.784 --> 00:18:25.200
And the result is we have much
better systems, much better

00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:28.770
product, and much
more motivated by it

00:18:28.770 --> 00:18:32.540
because nobody was penalized
for missing arbitrary numbers

00:18:32.540 --> 00:18:33.680
on arbitrary dates.

00:18:33.680 --> 00:18:38.490
So I'm learning how
to build and run

00:18:38.490 --> 00:18:39.990
a business for the infinite.

00:18:39.990 --> 00:18:42.510
When somebody asked me
recently in an interview

00:18:42.510 --> 00:18:44.190
about my competition,
like how do I

00:18:44.190 --> 00:18:47.860
compete against the people in
my space, the answer is, what--

00:18:47.860 --> 00:18:49.440
competing against what?

00:18:49.440 --> 00:18:50.699
What am I competing for?

00:18:50.699 --> 00:18:52.740
Like, am I going to compare
how many views on TED

00:18:52.740 --> 00:18:55.710
or how many book sales or how
much my personal income is

00:18:55.710 --> 00:18:57.270
or how much my
corporate income is?

00:18:57.270 --> 00:18:58.650
What's the arbitrary standard?

00:18:58.650 --> 00:19:01.890
Because I can be ahead on some
metrics and behind on others.

00:19:01.890 --> 00:19:05.540
I can drive myself crazy or it
can be really proud of myself.

00:19:05.540 --> 00:19:09.620
Worse, I'm choosing who
my competitive set is.

00:19:09.620 --> 00:19:13.880
But the competitor set is way
larger than I can imagine.

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:16.010
I love it when the
networks declare

00:19:16.010 --> 00:19:17.521
that they're number one.

00:19:17.521 --> 00:19:19.520
You do realize they're
only comparing themselves

00:19:19.520 --> 00:19:21.140
to the few other
networks that they

00:19:21.140 --> 00:19:22.264
want to compare themselves.

00:19:22.264 --> 00:19:25.110
NBC, ABC, CBS, and Fox compare
themselves to each other.

00:19:25.110 --> 00:19:34.260
They ignore Netflix, Hulu, HBO,
YouTube, and the rest of them.

00:19:34.260 --> 00:19:35.810
But that's the point.

00:19:35.810 --> 00:19:38.220
If you can make your
own competitive set,

00:19:38.220 --> 00:19:39.410
you will be number one.

00:19:39.410 --> 00:19:41.390
Everybody will have
their day in the sun.

00:19:41.390 --> 00:19:43.539
I get a kick out of that.

00:19:43.539 --> 00:19:44.580
I get a kick out of that.

00:19:44.580 --> 00:19:46.764
So especially for an
organization like YouTube,

00:19:46.764 --> 00:19:48.430
the question is, who's
your competition?

00:19:48.430 --> 00:19:50.070
The competition is yourself.

00:19:50.070 --> 00:19:51.557
Wish everybody the best of luck.

00:19:51.557 --> 00:19:52.890
Let them make their own metrics.

00:19:52.890 --> 00:19:54.180
Let them declare
themselves number one.

00:19:54.180 --> 00:19:54.930
Who cares?

00:19:54.930 --> 00:19:56.596
They'll fall out of
the game before you.

00:19:56.596 --> 00:19:57.870
That's the goal.

00:19:57.870 --> 00:20:00.440
That's the goal.

